    year = 2004,
    abstract = {This paper describes an optimal line detector for the one-dimensional
        case which is derived from Canny’s criteria, and an efficient approach for the
        detection of line junctions and line terminations. The line detector is extended
        to the two-dimensional case by operating separately in the x and y directions.
        An efficient implementation using an infinite impulse response (IIR) filter is
        provided. This implementation has the additional advantage that increasing the
        filter scale affects neither temporal nor spatial complexity. The detection
        algorithm for junctions and terminations is divided into two steps. First, given
        the lines extracted from the original image, a local measure of line curvature
        is estimated using the mean of the dot products of orientation vectors within a
        given neighbourhood. The second step involves the localization of junctions and
        terminations. Experimental results using several synthetic and real images
        demonstrate the validity of the two methods.},
}

